27
00:01:59,020 --> 00:02:01,980
You can also click on the citation buttons within the output,

28
00:02:02,380 --> 00:02:07,080
and it opens up a side window that also shows the original text from the Wikipedia article.

29
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:08,600
Let's do another check.

30
00:02:09,039 --> 00:02:11,880
It mentions a piece of art called Love is in the Bin.

31
00:02:12,360 --> 00:02:17,140
Here, if you click on the first citation, it doesn't seem to mention this piece of art.

32
00:02:17,360 --> 00:02:20,660
But for the next citation, it does mention this particular piece of artwork.

33
00:02:21,580 --> 00:02:24,540
And if you go to the original article, you can see it there too.

34
00:02:25,440 --> 00:02:29,240
So I hope you can see that having a chatbot read through an article first

35
00:02:29,540 --> 00:02:34,720
can really help you zoom in and focus on the topics or details that you're really interested in.

36
00:02:35,080 --> 00:02:39,800
And I hope you can also see how valuable it is to be able to reference the original source material.

37
00:02:40,300 --> 00:02:44,500
And I'll just mention that Balloon Girl is one of Banksy's most famous pieces of art,

38
00:02:44,760 --> 00:02:48,600
and it was transformed into another piece of art called Love is in the Bin.

39
00:02:48,920 --> 00:02:53,120
If you're curious to learn more, you can check out the Wikipedia article or ask a chatbot.

40
00:02:53,380 --> 00:02:57,120
You may find that if you use the keyword summarize for a task,

41
00:02:57,460 --> 00:03:03,120
then a chatbot may reply in its own words instead of providing direct quotes from the original source material.

42
00:03:03,700 --> 00:03:09,020
And since not all chatbots have the feature of linking citations to the original source,

43
00:03:09,420 --> 00:03:14,740
it may become a bit more difficult to verify if the chatbot's output is coming from the source document.

44
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:19,720
so you may prefer that it gives you word-for-word text from the source instead.

45
00:03:20,300 --> 00:03:23,200
One recommendation I have is, instead of saying summarize,

46
00:03:23,700 --> 00:03:28,020
you may want to ask it to extract relevant text as direct quotes.

47
00:03:28,520 --> 00:03:32,320
This encourages the chatbot to use the exact wording from the source material.

48
00:03:32,820 --> 00:03:37,960
One thing I've experienced is that sometimes it's not enough to only say extract relevant text.

49
00:03:38,320 --> 00:03:44,160
Sometimes it works better if you use this entire phrase, extract relevant text as direct quotes.

50
00:03:44,400 --> 00:03:48,860
to try to make it clear as possible that you want it to not try to summarize in its own words,

51
00:03:49,140 --> 00:03:51,160
but to really get the original wording from the source.

